  "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nI may be incorrect on my understanding of what should be correct behaviour here, however, the logic of `ResteasyReactiveScanner.scanForApplicationClass` seems to mean that if there are multiple Application classes, the method will exit at:\r\n\r\n```\r\n            if (selectedAppClass != null) {\r\n                throw new RuntimeException(\"More than one Application class: \" + applications);\r\n            }\r\n```\r\n\r\nhowever the `excludedClasses` list does not seem to be examined, meaning if you have multiple Application classes on your classpath it is impossible to use exclusions to remove one of them.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIf you have multiple Application classes, however all but 1 are excluded, do not throw an error and use the 1 Application class.\n\n### Actual behavior\n\nIf multiple Application classes are present, no matter what configuration you specify the application/build will fail.\n\n### How to Reproduce?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Output of `uname -a` or `ver`\n\n_No response_\n\n### Output of `java -version`\n\n_No response_\n\n### GraalVM version (if different from Java)\n\n_No response_\n\n### Quarkus version or git rev\n\n_No response_\n\n### Build tool (ie. output of `mvnw --version` or `gradlew --version`)\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional information\n\n_No response_",
